<b>Carrier oil</b>, also known as <b>base oil</b> or <b>vegetable oil</b>, is used to dilute <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../028/281028.xml">
essential oil</link>s and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../483/896483.xml">
absolutes</link> before they are applied to the skin.  They are so named because they <it>carry</it> the essential oil onto the skin.  Carrier oils do not contain a concentrated aroma, unlike essential oils, nor do they <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../303/10303.xml">
evaporate</link> like them.<p>

There are a range of different carrier oils each with their own individual properties and suitability towards different treatments in <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../ury/26th_century.xml">
aromatherapy</link>.  <it>Infused oils</it> are a combination of a carrier oil and various <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../296/13296.xml">
herb</link>s.</p>
<p>

True carrier oils are generally cold-pressed vegetable oils taken, amongst others:
